column6: Doctors shouldn’t underestimate the significant influence that patients’ negative expectations can have on outcome

column6: ..The findings suggest that doctors may need to consider dealing with patients’ beliefs about the effectiveness of any treatment, as well as determining which drug might be the best for that patient.. ..‘Doctors shouldn’t underestimate the significant influence that patients’ negative expectations can have on outcome.. ..people with chronic pain will often have seen many doctors and tried many drugs that haven’t worked for them.. ..They come to see the clinician with all this negative experience, not expecting to receive anything that will work for them.. ..Doctors have almost got to work on that first before any drug will have an effect on their pain.. ..We should control for the effect of people’s expectations on the results of any clinical trial.. ..At the very least we should make sure we minimise any negative expectations to make sure we’re not masking true efficacy in a trial drug..
